on, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1345–1414":"1345–1414","1352–Female":"1352–Deceased","1354–Female":"1354–Deceased","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1372–1412":"1372–1412","1380–1450":"1380–1450","–1450":"–1450","1310–1369":"1310–1369","–Female":"Deceased","before 1345":"before 1345","1352":"1352","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","3 August 1369":"3 August 1369","before September 1369":"before September 1369","1414":"1414","1369":"1369","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1310":"1310","1354":"1354","after 1399":"after 1399","1439":"1439","ABT 1380":"about 1380","Hesket in the Forest, Cumberland, England":"Hesket in the Forest, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Whitrigg, Cumberland, England":"Whitrigg, Cumberland, England","of Great Orton, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Orton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Orton in Cambridgeshire, Leicestershire, Northamptonshire, Warwickshire, and Westmorland. All those in England share a second element from Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’, but the first element in each case is more difficult to determine. Examples in Cambridgeshire and Warwickshire are on the banks of rivers, so these are probably derived from Old English <i>ōfer</i> ‘riverbank’; in other cases it is impossible to distinguish between <i>ofer</i> ‘ridge’ and <i>ufera</i> ‘upper’. Orton in Westmorland is probably formed with the Old Norse byname <i>Orri</i> ‘black-cock’ (the male black grouse). Orton near Fochabers, Scotland, is of uncertain etymology.","Americanized form of Norwegian <b>Årtun</b>: habitational name from the farm name Årtun, found in six places, e.g. in the province of Rogaland, a compound of the genitive case singular of Old Norse <i>á</i> ‘small river’ and <i>tún</i> ‘farm yard (surrounded by buildings)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Urton","meanings":["English (Derbyshire): variant of   Orton  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Orton was born in 1345 as the daughter of Giles Orton of Stainton and Maud. She married Sir Clement Skelton MP before September 1369. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 3 daughters. She died in 1414, in England, at the age of 69."},"et":{"1345–1414":"1345–1414","1352–Female":"1352–Surnud","1354–Female":"1354–Surnud","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1372–1412":"1372–1412","1380–1450":"1380–1450","–1450":"–1450","1310–1369":"1310–1369","–Female":"Surnud","before 1345":"enne 1345","1352":"1352","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1380","3 August 1369":"3. august 1369","before September 1369":"enne septembrit 1369","1414":"1414","1369":"1369","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1399":"1399","1310":"1310","1354":"1354","after 1399":"pärast 1399","1439":"1439","ABT 1380":"umbes 1380","Hesket in the Forest, Cumberland, England":"Hesket in the Forest, Cumberland, England","England":"England","Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England":"Stainton in Carlisle, Cumberland, England","Whitrigg, Cumberland, England":"Whitrigg, Cumberland, England","of Great Orton, Cumberland, England":"Great Orton, Cumberland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1345–1414":"1345–1414","1352–Female":"1352–Kuollut","1354–Female":"1354–Kuollut","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1370–1439":"1370–1439","1372–1412":"1372–1412","1380–1450":"1380–1450","–1450":"–1450","1310–1369":"1310–1369","–Female":"Kuollut","before 1345":"ennen vuotta 1345","1352":"1352","1450":"1450","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1380":"1